<!-- INTRO -->
<section id="intro">
  <div class="intro-visual reveal">
    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1611273426858-450d8e3c9fce?w=900&q=85" alt="Polluted river with industrial waste" loading="lazy"/>
    <div class="intro-overlay"></div>
    <span class="intro-img-label">Industrial Discharge · Yamuna River, Delhi</span>
  </div>
  <div class="intro-text">
    <p class="section-tag reveal">What Is Happening</p>
    <h2 class="intro-heading reveal">The World's Water Is Being <em>Poisoned</em> — Silently</h2>
    <p class="intro-body reveal">Water pollution occurs when harmful substances — chemicals, waste, plastics, pathogens — contaminate water bodies to the point where they become hazardous to humans, wildlife, and ecosystems. It is one of the world's most pervasive and deadly environmental crises, yet remains largely invisible to those not directly affected.</p>
    <p class="intro-body reveal">India is home to some of the world's most polluted rivers. The Central Pollution Control Board has identified over 350 polluted river stretches across the country. The Ganga alone carries the waste of over 500 million people — yet remains a lifeline for drinking, agriculture, and spiritual life.</p>
    <div class="quote-pull reveal">
      <p>"Water and sanitation are at the very core of sustainable development, critical to the survival of people and the planet."</p>
      <cite>— Ban Ki-moon, Former UN Secretary-General</cite>
    </div>
    <p class="intro-body reveal">Globally, contaminated water causes more deaths annually than war, terrorism, and all other forms of violence combined. Every minute, a child under five dies from a water-related disease. The science is clear; what is needed is political will and urgent action.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CAUSES -->
<section id="causes">
  <div class="causes-header">
    <div>
      <p class="section-tag reveal">Sources of Contamination</p>
      <h2 class="causes-heading reveal">What Is <em>Poisoning</em><br>Our Water?</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="causes-subtext reveal">Water bodies worldwide are under siege from multiple simultaneous pollution sources — industrial, agricultural, domestic, and plastic — creating a compound crisis with no single fix.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="causes-grid">
    <div class="cause-card reveal">
      <img class="cause-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1504711434969-e33886168f5c?w=600&q=80" alt="Industrial effluent discharge pipe"/>
      <div class="cause-num">01</div>
      <h3 class="cause-title">Industrial Effluents</h3>
      <p class="cause-text">Factories discharge heavy metals (mercury, lead, arsenic), acids, dyes, and toxic solvents directly into rivers. India alone has over 50,000 industrial units releasing effluents, with textile and tannery clusters among the most destructive — the Bandi River in Rajasthan turns chemically-coloured seasonally.</p>
      <span class="cause-badge">70% Dumped Untreated in Developing Nations</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cause-card reveal">
      <img class="cause-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1500595046743-cd271d694d30?w=600&q=80" alt="Agricultural fields with fertilizer runoff"/>
      <div class="cause-num">02</div>
      <h3 class="cause-title">Agricultural Runoff</h3>
      <p class="cause-text">Excess fertilisers (nitrogen, phosphorus), pesticides, and herbicides from farms flow into waterways, triggering algal blooms that deplete oxygen and create dead zones. India uses 17.5 million tonnes of fertilisers annually — much of it ending up in the Ganga-Brahmaputra basin.</p>
      <span class="cause-badge">~60% of River Nitrogen from Agriculture</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cause-card reveal">
      <img class="cause-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1530981418487-31c371b3d3ca?w=600&q=80" alt="Sewage flowing into water"/>
      <div class="cause-num">03</div>
      <h3 class="cause-title">Untreated Sewage</h3>
      <p class="cause-text">India generates about 72,368 MLD of sewage daily but only has treatment capacity for 31,841 MLD. Pathogens in raw sewage — cholera, typhoid, hepatitis A — claim hundreds of thousands of lives each year. Urban slums and riverbank communities bear the heaviest burden.</p>
      <span class="cause-badge">Only 44% of India's Sewage Treated</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cause-card reveal">
      <img class="cause-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1530521954074-e64f6810b32d?w=600&q=80" alt="Plastic waste floating in ocean"/>
      <div class="cause-num">04</div>
      <h3 class="cause-title">Plastic Pollution</h3>
      <p class="cause-text">11 million tonnes of plastic enter the oceans annually — a figure set to triple by 2040. Microplastics have been found in the deepest ocean trenches and in human blood. India is among the top contributors, generating 3.5 million tonnes of plastic waste per year with inadequate collection systems.</p>
      <span class="cause-badge">11M Tonnes Enter Oceans Every Year</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cause-card reveal">
      <img class="cause-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1569163139599-0f4517e36f51?w=600&q=80" alt="Mining waste in river"/>
      <div class="cause-num">05</div>
      <h3 class="cause-title">Mining & Acid Drainage</h3>
      <p class="cause-text">Mining operations expose sulphide minerals to air and water, generating sulphuric acid that leaches toxic metals — cadmium, zinc, arsenic — into groundwater and rivers. The Damodar River in Jharkhand-West Bengal carries decades of coal and coal washing effluents, earning it the name "River of Sorrow."</p>
      <span class="cause-badge">Damodar: 75+ years of contamination</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cause-card reveal">
      <img class="cause-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1509629927-58a7b3a3a5bb?w=600&q=80" alt="Religious offerings floating in river"/>
      <div class="cause-num">06</div>
      <h3 class="cause-title">Religious & Solid Waste</h3>
      <p class="cause-text">Millions of tonnes of solid waste — including flower offerings, idols, unburnt bodies, and cremation ash — are immersed in Indian rivers annually as part of cultural and religious practices. While individually small, the cumulative biochemical impact on rivers like the Ganga is significant and measurable.</p>
      <span class="cause-badge">500M People Depend on the Ganga</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CONSEQUENCES -->
<section id="consequences">
  <div class="cons-intro">
    <p class="section-tag reveal">The Human & Ecological Toll</p>
    <h2 class="reveal">Devastating Consequences<br>Across <em>Every Life System</em></h2>
  </div>

  <div class="con-row reveal">
    <div class="con-img">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559825481-12a05cc00344?w=900&q=85" alt="Child drinking contaminated water"/>
      <div class="con-img-num">01</div>
      <span class="con-img-badge">Public Health Emergency</span>
    </div>
    <div class="con-text">
      <p class="section-tag">Health</p>
      <h3>Contaminated Water Is a<br><em>Silent Killer</em></h3>
      <p>Waterborne diseases — diarrhoea, cholera, typhoid, dysentery — kill approximately 3.5 million people per year, with children under five most vulnerable. In India, waterborne diseases account for 37.7 million cases annually, creating a massive healthcare burden concentrated in the poorest communities.</p>
      <p>Heavy metal contamination — arsenic in West Bengal's groundwater, fluoride in Rajasthan — causes chronic conditions including cancer, neurological damage, and skeletal fluorosis affecting millions who have no alternative water source.</p>
      <div class="con-stat-box">
        <div class="con-stat"><div class="n">3.5M</div><div class="l">Deaths Per Year Globally</div></div>
        <div class="con-stat"><div class="n">37.7M</div><div class="l">Waterborne Cases in India/yr</div></div>
        <div class="con-stat"><div class="n">1 in 5</div><div class="l">Child Deaths from Water Disease</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="con-row reveal">
    <div class="con-img">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1548550023-2bdb3c5beed7?w=900&q=85" alt="Dead fish in polluted water, algal bloom"/>
      <div class="con-img-num">02</div>
      <span class="con-img-badge">Aquatic Ecosystem Collapse</span>
    </div>
    <div class="con-text">
      <p class="section-tag">Biodiversity</p>
      <h3>River Ecosystems Are<br><em>Dying</em> Stretch by Stretch</h3>
      <p>Oxygen-depleted "dead zones" caused by algal blooms from excess nutrients have created over 500 aquatic dead zones globally, covering an area larger than the United Kingdom. In India, the Sabarmati, Musi, and portions of the Ganga carry virtually no aquatic life in their heavily polluted urban stretches.</p>
      <p>The Gangetic river dolphin — India's national aquatic animal — faces critical endangerment from pollution, entanglement, and habitat destruction. Its population has declined by over 50% in the past three decades.</p>
      <div class="con-stat-box">
        <div class="con-stat"><div class="n">500+</div><div class="l">Ocean Dead Zones</div></div>
        <div class="con-stat"><div class="n">-50%</div><div class="l">Gangetic Dolphin Population</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="con-row reveal">
    <div class="con-img">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1504208434309-cb69f4fe52b0?w=900&q=85" alt="Parched land, failed crops"/>
      <div class="con-img-num">03</div>
      <span class="con-img-badge">Food Security Threat</span>
    </div>
    <div class="con-text">
      <p class="section-tag">Agriculture</p>
      <h3>Polluted Irrigation Is<br>Entering Our <em>Food</em></h3>
      <p>Over 20 million hectares globally are irrigated with wastewater — a practice that deposits heavy metals, pathogens, and pharmaceutical residues directly into soil and food crops. In peri-urban India, vegetables grown with Yamuna water near Delhi show alarming levels of lead, cadmium, and faecal coliforms.</p>
      <p>Groundwater contamination from agricultural chemicals and industrial leaching renders aquifers unusable across vast regions. In Punjab, widespread pesticide contamination has created cancer clusters in what locals call the "Cancer Train" belt.</p>
      <div class="con-stat-box">
        <div class="con-stat"><div class="n">20M ha</div><div class="l">Wastewater-Irrigated Land</div></div>
        <div class="con-stat"><div class="n">600M</div><div class="l">Indians Lack Safe Groundwater</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="con-row reveal">
    <div class="con-img">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1601024445121-e5b82f020549?w=900&q=85" alt="Economic cost of water pollution"/>
      <div class="con-img-num">04</div>
      <span class="con-img-badge">Economic Devastation</span>
    </div>
    <div class="con-text">
      <p class="section-tag">Economy</p>
      <h3>Water Pollution Costs the<br>World <em>Trillions</em></h3>
      <p>The World Bank estimates water insecurity and pollution cost the global economy $500 billion annually through reduced productivity, healthcare costs, and tourism losses. India loses approximately $6.7 billion per year to water pollution impacts — with the fishing, tourism, and agricultural sectors hardest hit.</p>
