<!-- TIMELINE -->
<section id="timeline">
  <p class="section-tag reveal">A Chronicle of Contamination</p>
  <h2 class="reveal">Decades of <em>Warnings</em><br>Largely Unheeded</h2>
  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="tl-item reveal">
      <div class="tl-year">1948</div>
      <div class="tl-dot-wrap"><div class="tl-dot"></div></div>
      <div class="tl-body"><h3>Ganga Pollution First Documented</h3><p>Post-independence India begins large-scale industrialisation. Scientists first document alarming levels of faecal contamination in the Ganga at Varanasi, marking the beginning of a systematic decline that accelerates with every decade of unchecked growth.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item reveal">
      <div class="tl-year">1974</div>
      <div class="tl-dot-wrap"><div class="tl-dot"></div></div>
      <div class="tl-body"><h3>Water (Prevention & Control of Pollution) Act</h3><p>India's landmark legislation creates the Central Pollution Control Board. Despite being a legal framework for water protection, enforcement remains chronically weak, with most industrial units flouting norms for decades without consequences.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item reveal">
      <div class="tl-year">1986</div>
      <div class="tl-dot-wrap"><div class="tl-dot warn"></div></div>
      <div class="tl-body"><h3>Ganga Action Plan Launched</h3><p>India's first large-scale river cleanup initiative, costing ₹902 crore, targets 25 cities on the Ganga. Independent assessments later find the plan had little measurable impact — pollution levels continued rising through the 1990s due to inadequate maintenance and rapid urban growth.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item reveal">
      <div class="tl-year">2005</div>
      <div class="tl-dot-wrap"><div class="tl-dot hot"></div></div>
      <div class="tl-body"><h3>WHO: 1.8M Child Deaths from Water Disease</h3><p>WHO reports that waterborne diarrhoea kills 1.8 million children under five each year globally — more than HIV/AIDS and malaria combined. The vast majority are in South and Southeast Asia, with India accounting for a disproportionate share.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item reveal">
      <div class="tl-year">2015</div>
      <div class="tl-dot-wrap"><div class="tl-dot warn"></div></div>
      <div class="tl-body"><h3>Namami Gange Programme — ₹20,000 Crore</h3><p>India's most ambitious river rejuvenation programme is launched with a massive budget. By 2024, progress includes new sewage treatment plants and solid waste management, but the Ganga remains polluted in major urban stretches, with the Delhi–Kanpur corridor persistently critical.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item reveal">
      <div class="tl-year">2023</div>
      <div class="tl-dot-wrap"><div class="tl-dot hot"></div></div>
      <div class="tl-body"><h3>CPCB: 351 Polluted River Stretches Identified</h3><p>India's Central Pollution Control Board releases its most comprehensive assessment yet — 351 river stretches are polluted, up from 302 in 2018. Maharashtra leads with 55 polluted stretches, followed by Assam, Madhya Pradesh, and Uttar Pradesh. The trend is worsening.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item reveal">
      <div class="tl-year">2030</div>
      <div class="tl-dot-wrap"><div class="tl-dot warn"></div></div>
      <div class="tl-body"><h3>SDG 6 Deadline: Safe Water for All</h3><p>The United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 6 commits all nations to ensuring clean water and sanitation for all by 2030. At current trajectories, neither India nor the global community is on track. The deadline is five years away — the gap between aspiration and reality has never been wider.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SOLUTIONS -->
<section id="solutions">
  <div class="solutions-header">
    <div>
      <p class="section-tag reveal">The Way Forward</p>
      <h2 class="reveal">Evidence-Based<br><em>Solutions</em> Exist</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="reveal">The technology and policy frameworks to solve water pollution are well-understood. The challenge is political will, equitable financing, and enforcement — not a lack of knowledge about what needs to be done.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="solutions-grid">
    <div class="sol-card reveal">
      <div class="sol-img"><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558618666-fcd25c85cd64?w=600&q=80" alt="Sewage treatment plant" loading="lazy"/></div>
      <div class="sol-body"><span class="sol-num">01 — Infrastructure</span><h3>Sewage Treatment Scale-Up</h3><p>India needs to more than double its sewage treatment capacity to close the 40,000+ MLD gap between generation and treatment. Decentralised treatment systems — including constructed wetlands and biodigesters — offer scalable, lower-cost solutions for smaller urban centres and rural areas.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="sol-card reveal">
      <div class="sol-img"><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1464226184884-fa280b87c399?w=600&q=80" alt="Organic farming with water conservation" loading="lazy"/></div>
      <div class="sol-body"><span class="sol-num">02 — Agriculture</span><h3>Clean Farming Practices</h3><p>Transitioning to precision agriculture, drip irrigation, organic farming, and buffer zones along waterways can dramatically reduce fertiliser and pesticide runoff. Zero-liquid-discharge mandates for agricultural zones near rivers could protect downstream communities at relatively low cost.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="sol-card reveal">
      <div class="sol-img"><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1509391366360-2e959784a276?w=600&q=80" alt="Industrial effluent treatment" loading="lazy"/></div>
      <div class="sol-body"><span class="sol-num">03 — Industry</span><h3>Zero Liquid Discharge</h3><p>Mandating Zero Liquid Discharge (ZLD) for textile, tannery, chemical, and pharmaceutical industries — as increasingly required in India's National Green Tribunal orders — prevents effluents from reaching waterways. Real-time online monitoring systems can detect violations instantly.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="sol-card reveal">
      <div class="sol-img"><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1530521954074-e64f6810b32d?w=600&q=80" alt="Plastic waste collection from river" loading="lazy"/></div>
      <div class="sol-body"><span class="sol-num">04 — Plastic</span><h3>Plastic Reduction & Interception</h3><p>River plastic interception systems, extended producer responsibility policies, and single-use plastic bans form a multi-layered approach. Nations that have implemented comprehensive bans — Rwanda, the EU — demonstrate that policy-led plastic reduction is achievable within a decade.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="sol-card reveal">
      <div class="sol-img"><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1448375240586-882707db888b?w=600&q=80" alt="Wetland restoration for water purification" loading="lazy"/></div>
      <div class="sol-body"><span class="sol-num">05 — Nature</span><h3>Wetland & Riparian Restoration</h3><p>Natural wetlands can filter up to 90% of water contaminants. Restoring floodplains, riparian buffers, and urban lakes provides free, resilient water treatment infrastructure. India has lost 30% of its wetland area since 1970; restoring even a fraction would yield massive water quality dividends.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="sol-card reveal">
      <div class="sol-img"><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1454165804606-c3d57bc86b40?w=600&q=80" alt="Water policy and governance" loading="lazy"/></div>
      <div class="sol-body"><span class="sol-num">06 — Governance</span><h3>Enforcement & Water Rights</h3><p>Real-time pollution monitoring, independent judicial oversight, community water rights recognition, and criminal penalties for industrial polluters are non-negotiable. Countries with the cleanest water — Switzerland, Finland, Denmark — share rigorous independent regulatory regimes that prioritise public health over industrial profit.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

